<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-payroll-direct-deposit-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What direct deposit in QuickBooks Payroll does.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qb-payroll-direct-deposit-in-brief-text">Direct deposit in QuickBooks Online Payroll pays your employees electronically &mdash; the net pay for each run is debited from your verified company bank account and deposited into each employee&rsquo;s bank account, replacing paper checks. It runs on top of the same payroll you already process: you enter or approve hours and amounts, and direct deposit handles how the money gets there. Behind the scenes the actual movement of funds is carried out by Intuit&rsquo;s payroll service on a fixed processing schedule &mdash; QuickBooks is where you set it up and approve the run.</p>
      <p>That split matters. Setting direct deposit up correctly &mdash; a verified company account, accurate employee bank details, a signed authorization on file, and a run approved before the cutoff &mdash; is the part you (or a ProAdvisor) control. The <em>processing</em> of the deposit, the lead time, and the release of funds on the pay date are Intuit&rsquo;s service to perform; an independent firm can&rsquo;t accelerate, release, or guarantee a transfer. What an independent ProAdvisor firm <em>can</em> do is make sure the setup is right, the cutoff is met, and payroll reconciles cleanly to the bank afterward.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

